# -*- mode:org;coding:utf-8 -*-
#+TITLE: nav edit: "sedit parse: unterminated list" when the function's last body form is a bare atom
#+AUTHOR: Pascal J. Bourguignon
#+DATE: 2026-07-22

* Symptom

At a stop in a function whose LAST body form is a bare atom, an editing
word (=edit=, =replace=, …) in the navigator fails with

: Error while executing the command: sedit parse: unterminated list

instead of opening the editor.

* Repro

: (defun id (a) a)
: (defun frob (x / z)
:   (setq z (id x))
:   z)                      ; <- bare-atom tail

Load instrumented (with source tracking, file on disk), break at FROB's
entry, then type =edit= at the NAV> prompt.

* Cause

=NAV-FORM-SPAN= (autolisp-debug-ui/source/navigator.lisp) computes the
root form's verbatim extent from the positions of its POSITIONED
sub-nodes. Interned runtime symbols are shared singletons and carry no
per-occurrence source position, so a bare-atom tail (the =z= on line 4)
contributes nothing and the computed end-line stops at the last
positioned LIST form (line 3). =NAV-FORM-SOURCE-TEXT= then extracts
lines 2–3 — an unterminated =(defun= — and =sedit parse= rejects it.

* Fix ideas

- Scan forward from the span's last line with the same
  paren/string/comment balancer =%NAV-FORM-END= already uses for the
  selection's closing bracket, and extend the end-line to the form's
  real close.
- Or record an explicit end position for the toplevel form at read time
  (the reader knows it) in the function metadata.
